ln this note the personal and the artistic motives are successfully combined. Both must be kept in mind in the interpretation of it. The fact that it was deliberately selected for publication is awarning against taking the personal clement too seriously 3 doubtless the bit of advice at the end had a real meaning, but neither that nor the expressions of discontent which skillfully pave the way for the advice should be over- iuterpreted. The warning is a very general one, such as might be addressed to many young men, and the sense of dissatisfaction with · himself and his work is more than once expressed by Horace.
